(43, 5, 12, 40, 21, 23, 23, 'Take up thy bed, and walk', 'Authority and Healing', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority in both passages. In John 5:12, the question of who commanded the healing is raised, paralleling Matthew 21:23, where the authority of Jesus is questioned.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 12, 7, 6, 29, 29, 'What man is that', 'Inquiry About Actions', 'This connection highlights the theme of inquiry regarding actions taken by individuals. Both passages feature characters asking, ''Who hath done this thing?'' and ''What man is that,'' emphasizing the curiosity and investigation surrounding significant acts.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 12, 45, 10, 2, 2, 'Take up thy bed, and walk', 'Zeal and Understanding in Faith', 'This connection highlights the theme of misunderstanding in faith. In John 5:12, the question reflects a lack of understanding about the authority behind the command to ''Take up thy bed, and walk,'' while Romans 10:2 addresses zeal without knowledge.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 12, 9, 14, 38, 38, NULL, 'Inquiry and Accountability', 'This connection highlights the theme of questioning authority and accountability in both passages. In John 5:12, the inquiry about who commanded the healing reflects a search for responsibility, while in 1 Samuel 14:38, Saul seeks to identify the source of sin among the people.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 13, 42, 4, 30, 30, 'conveyed himself away', 'Jesus'' Disappearance', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' ability to move away unnoticed. In John, Jesus conveys himself away, while in Luke, he passes through the midst of the crowd. This connection highlights his elusive presence in critical moments.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 13, 42, 24, 31, 31, NULL, 'Vanishing of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the mysterious nature of Jesus'' presence and departure in both passages. In John 5:13, Jesus conveys himself away, while in Luke 24:31, he vanishes out of sight.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 13, 43, 8, 59, 59, 'Jesus had conveyed himself away', 'Jesus Conceals Himself', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus concealing himself from those around him. In both passages, Jesus is described as having hidden or conveyed himself away from the multitude or the people seeking to harm him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 13, 43, 14, 9, 9, 'wist not who it was', 'Recognition of Jesus'' Identity', 'This connection highlights the theme of recognition in both passages. In John 5:13, the healed man does not know Jesus, while in John 14:9, Jesus emphasizes the importance of recognizing Him as the revelation of the Father.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 14, 43, 8, 11, 11, 'sin no more', 'Call to Avoid Sin', 'Both passages emphasize the instruction to ''sin no more'' after receiving forgiveness or healing. This connection highlights the theme of moral responsibility following divine intervention.', 'theme', 0.46799999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 14, 3, 26, 23, 24, 'sin no more', 'Sin and Consequences', 'This connection highlights the theme of sin and its consequences. Both passages emphasize the need to avoid sin to prevent further punishment or worse outcomes.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 14, 19, 118, 18, 18, 'sin no more, lest a worse thing come unto thee', 'Connection of Sin and Chastening', 'This connection highlights the theme of sin and its consequences. Both passages emphasize the idea of being chastened or warned to avoid worse outcomes, linking the concept of sin to divine discipline.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 14, 16, 9, 28, 28, 'sin no more', 'Sin and Consequences', 'This connection highlights the theme of sin leading to negative consequences. In John 5:14, Jesus warns against sinning again, while Nehemiah 9:28 recounts how the people did evil and faced the dominion of their enemies.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 14, 40, 12, 45, 45, 'sin no more, lest a worse thing come unto thee', 'Warning Against Sin and Consequences', 'This connection highlights the theme of sin and its consequences. Both passages emphasize the idea that failing to avoid sin can lead to a worse state than before.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 14, 19, 107, 20, 22, 'made whole', 'Healing and Praise Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of healing and the call to praise God for His goodness. Both passages emphasize the importance of being made whole and responding with thanksgiving and rejoicing.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 14, 66, 2, 21, 23, 'sin no more', 'Sin and Consequences', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of repentance and the consequences of sin. In John, Jesus warns against sinning again after healing, while Revelation speaks of judgment for unrepentant sin. This connection highlights the serious nature of sin and the call to repentance.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 15, 43, 4, 29, 29, 'made him whole', 'Recognition of Jesus'' Identity', 'This connection highlights the theme of recognizing Jesus as the Messiah. In both passages, individuals acknowledge Jesus'' role in their lives, with the man identifying Jesus as the one who made him whole and the woman proclaiming Him as the Christ.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 15, 43, 9, 11, 12, 'made him whole', 'Healing and Testimony Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of healing performed by Jesus and the subsequent testimony of those healed. In John 5:15, the healed man identifies Jesus as the one who made him whole, while in John 9:11, the man who received sight also attributes his healing to Jesus.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 15, 41, 1, 45, 45, 'made him whole', 'Publicizing Jesus'' Miracles', 'This connection highlights the theme of individuals spreading the news of Jesus'' miraculous works. In both passages, the actions of the healed man and the leper lead to increased attention on Jesus, affecting his ability to move freely.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 15, 43, 1, 19, 19, NULL, 'Connection of Testimony and Identity', 'This connection highlights the theme of testimony in both passages. In John 5:15, the man testifies about Jesus, while in John 1:19, the priests and Levites seek to understand John''s identity, indicating a broader context of revealing who Jesus is.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 15, 43, 5, 12, 12, 'made him whole', 'Connection of Healing and Inquiry', 'Both passages emphasize the act of healing and the subsequent inquiry about the healer. The question in John 5:12 about ''What man is that'' directly relates to the revelation in John 5:15 that it was Jesus who made the man whole.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 16, 43, 10, 39, 39, 'sought to slay him', 'Persecution of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the Jews'' intent to harm Jesus due to his actions on the Sabbath. The connection highlights the ongoing conflict between Jesus and the Jewish authorities, culminating in their repeated attempts to seize him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 16, 40, 12, 13, 13, 'on the sabbath day', 'Healing on the Sabbath', 'Both passages emphasize actions taken on the Sabbath that provoke conflict. In John 5:16, Jesus is persecuted for healing on the Sabbath, while Matthew 12:13 illustrates a similar healing act that demonstrates His authority over Sabbath laws.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 16, 41, 3, 6, 6, 'sought to slay him', 'Persecution of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the plot against Jesus due to his actions on the Sabbath. In John 5:16, the Jews sought to slay him, while in Mark 3:6, the Pharisees conspired to destroy him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 16, 42, 6, 11, 11, 'sought to slay him', 'Persecution of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the hostility towards Jesus due to his actions on the Sabbath. In John, the Jews sought to slay him, while in Luke, they were filled with madness and plotted against him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 16, 43, 5, 13, 13, 'sought to slay him, because he had done these things on the sabbath day', 'Healing and Sabbath Controversy', 'This connection highlights the reaction of the Jews to Jesus'' actions on the Sabbath. The healing mentioned in John 5:13 leads to the persecution noted in John 5:16.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 16, 44, 9, 4, 5, 'persecute Jesus', 'Persecution of Jesus Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of persecution faced by Jesus and later by Saul, who is confronted for his actions against Jesus'' followers. Both passages emphasize the conflict arising from religious practices and beliefs, particularly regarding the Sabbath.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
